It's time for Month 5 in the Traverse BOM, and that means making some hourglass blocks! I came up with this block quite a few years ago when I was making a quilt for Color Collective and I couldn't quite figure out how to piece it without it being overly complicated. Finally, I realized that if I trimmed an hourglass block, it would give me exactly the look I wanted! 
I spent a fair amount of time messing around with the design on the computer and I love how if you offset the trimmed blocks when sewn into rows, you get the interesting shape interaction that we now have in the Traverse Quilt. 
I hope you all enjoy it! The monthly giveaway winner will be announced tomorrow too.

✨Class open for sign ups✨
So many of you have asked for this one, and I thought it was the perfect fit for summer! I'm excited to announce that I will be offering my Four Patch Quilt in a live Zoom workshop.
 
This quilt began when I was in a bit of a sewing slump. One of the ways I get through a rut is to just sew something simple and mindless without an end result in mind. I just started sewing four patches without a worry about how do these go together or what am I going to do with them? And when I finally had enough of them to think that over, my creativity wasn't feeling so weighed down because the little humble four patch had energized me. 
 
What this quilt really became about was playing with color and value, and it became a lot about design. So this class is a four patch, but really it's a design class where we will go into using a basic block and coming out with a design that is totally unique to you and your design aesthetic and your color sense.

CLASS A: Thursdays June 29 & July 6
CLASS B: Mondays July 10 & 17

You can sign up using the link in my profile, and as always the class comes with a pattern and will be recorded so you can watch it all summer long.

Do you want to join me for a  fun afternoon of English Paper Piecing?  English paper piecing (EPP) is a great technique to add to your toolbox if you aren’t already familiar with it. There are very few tools you need and the slow pace of stitching can be incredibly relaxing and rewarding. The applications for complex piecing open up a whole new world of possibilities! There is a bit of a learning curve with EPP but after a few blocks you start to get a familiarity with the technique and it becomes much easier. In this class, I'll cover the basics of hand sewing, and how to use color and value to create a dynamic design.
